00:14:35,300 --> 00:14:39,267
In fact, she outlived
all her brothers by 30 years,

260
00:14:39,300 --> 00:14:41,967
basically because
she didn't drink.

261
00:14:42,000 --> 00:14:45,100
There's lots of ways
to die from alcoholism--

262
00:14:45,133 --> 00:14:47,767
liver disease,
car accidents, sure--

263
00:14:47,800 --> 00:14:51,333
but smalley men
fall off the roof.

264
00:14:51,367 --> 00:14:52,667
Whoa!

265
00:14:52,700 --> 00:14:54,033
[Crash]

266
00:14:54,067 --> 00:14:57,600
In fact, three smalley men
have met their maker

267
00:14:57,633 --> 00:15:00,333
while changing
the storm window.

268
00:15:00,367 --> 00:15:02,267
Actually, that's not true.

269
00:15:02,300 --> 00:15:04,767
Uncle frank
got smashed one afternoon

270
00:15:04,800 --> 00:15:09,267
and went up on the roof
to trim the big elm.

271
00:15:09,300 --> 00:15:14,333
The doctor said he was dead
well before he hit the ground.

272
00:15:14,367 --> 00:15:16,267
So death is something

273
00:15:16,300 --> 00:15:19,333
we smalleys
can pretty much deal with.

274
00:15:19,367 --> 00:15:21,833
It's life that seems to be

275
00:15:21,867 --> 00:15:23,333
the problem.

276
00:15:23,367 --> 00:15:25,533
Take, for example,

277
00:15:25,567 --> 00:15:27,800
my pot-smoking,
unemployed brother Donnie.

278
00:15:29,433 --> 00:15:32,400
I thought Jodie
was picking me up.

279
00:15:32,433 --> 00:15:34,400
Tommy slashed
her tires again.

280
00:15:34,433 --> 00:15:36,900
But she got
a restraining order.

281
00:15:36,933 --> 00:15:38,900
Yeah.

282
00:15:38,933 --> 00:15:40,900
Well, not to be
judgmental,

283
00:15:40,933 --> 00:15:43,900
but he is the worst
ex-husband yet.

284
00:15:43,933 --> 00:15:46,400
How's dad?
What's he up to?

285
00:15:46,433 --> 00:15:48,400
About a quart a day.

286
00:15:48,433 --> 00:15:50,900
Mom's the one
that's driving me crazy.

287
00:15:50,933 --> 00:15:53,400
Believe me,
the minute I find work,

288
00:15:53,433 --> 00:15:54,900
I am history!

289
00:15:54,933 --> 00:15:58,400
Well, this trip,
I promised myself
to simply detach.

290
00:15:58,433 --> 00:16:01,400
Now, this trip
is about aunt Paula

291
00:16:01,433 --> 00:16:03,900
and honoring her
and remembering her,

292
00:16:03,933 --> 00:16:06,900
and I simply
refuse to get enmeshed
in the family craziness.

293
00:16:06,933 --> 00:16:10,300
I'm going to
let go and let god
and just stay serene.

294
00:16:10,333 --> 00:16:12,400
[Revving motorcycle engine]

295
00:16:12,433 --> 00:16:15,333
I totaled the accord.
Hop on.

296
00:16:18,433 --> 00:16:22,633
I thought Minnesota
had a helmet law!

297
00:16:23,967 --> 00:16:26,100
* mucha muchacha

298
00:16:26,133 --> 00:16:27,600
* mucha muchacha

299
00:16:27,633 --> 00:16:30,667
* mucha muchacha

300
00:16:30,700 --> 00:16:32,467
* mucha muchacha *

301
00:16:33,800 --> 00:16:36,767
they say you can't
go home again.

302
00:16:36,800 --> 00:16:41,267
In my case, make that
you're crazy to go home again.

303
00:16:41,300 --> 00:16:44,767
Seeing my mother is always like
a trip to the dentist

304
00:16:44,800 --> 00:16:46,900
before the advent
of modern painkillers.

305
00:16:46,933 --> 00:16:47,900
Hi, mom.

306
00:16:47,933 --> 00:16:49,900
Hi. Oh,
be careful,
honey.

307
00:16:49,933 --> 00:16:52,400
You don't
want to get
splattered.

308
00:16:52,433 --> 00:16:53,900
Well, you've
been busy--

309
00:16:53,933 --> 00:16:55,400
lots of food.

310
00:16:55,433 --> 00:16:56,900
Well, as a rule,

311
00:16:56,933 --> 00:16:59,400
it's better
to have too much
than too little,

312
00:16:59,433 --> 00:17:01,900
or maybe I just
don't know

313
00:17:01,933 --> 00:17:03,900
how to cook
for a funeral.

314
00:17:03,933 --> 00:17:05,900
I didn't mean to be
critical, mom.

315
00:17:05,933 --> 00:17:07,400
It's just that,
you know,

316
00:17:07,433 --> 00:17:09,400
we're going to have,
like, 20 people.

317
00:17:09,433 --> 00:17:12,400
Aunt Paula died,
not, you know,
the queen of england.

318
00:17:12,433 --> 00:17:15,400
Now, what is that comment
supposed to mean?

319
00:17:15,433 --> 00:17:17,400
I'm sorry.
I didn't--

320
00:17:17,433 --> 00:17:19,900
it's a beautiful
spread, mom,

321
00:17:19,933 --> 00:17:22,400
and I owe you
an amends.

322
00:17:22,433 --> 00:17:23,900
Amends?

323
00:17:23,933 --> 00:17:26,900
Is that one of
those funny words

324
00:17:26,933 --> 00:17:29,900
that you use
in your little
TV show?

325
00:17:29,933 --> 00:17:34,400
Well, um, actually,
I'm not going to be
doing that anymore.

326
00:17:34,433 --> 00:17:37,100
It's kind of
a mutual decision.

327
00:17:37,133 --> 00:17:38,733
They fired him.

328
00:17:38,767 --> 00:17:43,200
Oh, I told you
that would happen,
didn't I?

329
00:17:43,233 --> 00:17:45,400
Oh, yeah, you did.

330
00:17:45,433 --> 00:17:48,400
I hope that
that helped
to prepare you

331
00:17:48,433 --> 00:17:50,300
for the disappointment.

332
00:17:52,033 --> 00:17:54,400
Oh, well,
what is this?

333
00:17:54,433 --> 00:17:57,400
Oh, I'm sorry, mom.
It's my journal.

334
00:17:57,433 --> 00:17:59,900
In fact,
I just got it.

335
00:17:59,933 --> 00:18:02,900
I plan to write down
everything that
happens to me--

336
00:18:02,933 --> 00:18:04,900
you know,
how I feel about things.

337
00:18:04,933 --> 00:18:07,667
It's going to be
pretty much the story
of my life.

338
00:18:07,700 --> 00:18:11,733
I got a good title for it--
waste of space.

339
00:18:11,767 --> 00:18:13,867
Ha ha ha!

340
00:18:13,900 --> 00:18:16,200
Hi, dad.

341
00:18:16,233 --> 00:18:17,800
Uh-huh.

342
00:18:17,833 --> 00:18:19,100
Waste of space. Nice.

343
00:18:19,133 --> 00:18:21,667
That's what dad
always called me

344
00:18:21,700 --> 00:18:23,933
when I was growing up.

345
00:18:23,967 --> 00:18:27,000
Hey, dad,
what do you say
you and me tomorrow,

346
00:18:27,033 --> 00:18:28,567
we get
really loaded,

347
00:18:28,600 --> 00:18:30,733
we go up
on the roof,

348
00:18:30,767 --> 00:18:32,367
change
the storm windows?

349
00:18:32,400 --> 00:18:35,400
Nobody's changing
any windows tomorrow.

350
00:18:35,433 --> 00:18:37,633
We got a funeral.

351
00:18:42,300 --> 00:18:44,833
Seeing aunt Paula
in that coffin

352
00:18:44,867 --> 00:18:46,767
hit me pretty hard,

353
00:18:46,800 --> 00:18:51,900
but my sister Jodie
went right into a lumbar spasm.

354
00:18:51,933 --> 00:18:56,400
You know, aunt Paula
was the best person
in this entire family,

355
00:18:56,433 --> 00:18:58,600
and nobody gives a damn.

356
00:18:58,633 --> 00:19:00,900
I mean, dad hated her,

357
00:19:00,933 --> 00:19:04,400
Donnie just thinks
this is one big joke,

358
00:19:04,433 --> 00:19:08,967
and, well,
all mom cares about
is her stupid glazed ham.

359
00:19:10,233 --> 00:19:12,400
You know,
Jodie, I think
all this stress

360
00:19:12,433 --> 00:19:14,300
is going
right to your back--

361
00:19:14,333 --> 00:19:18,100
I mean,
raising a son
all on your own,

362
00:19:18,133 --> 00:19:20,900
Tommy slashing
your tires,

363
00:19:20,933 --> 00:19:24,633
you know,
and your weight--

364
00:19:24,667 --> 00:19:26,400
more of the stress--

365
00:19:26,433 --> 00:19:28,500
so I was thinking,
well--

366
00:19:28,533 --> 00:19:31,567
Stuart, I am not going

367
00:19:31,600 --> 00:19:34,600
to an overeaters
anonymous meeting.

368
00:19:34,633 --> 00:19:37,833
O.k., forget
I said it.

369
00:19:42,433 --> 00:19:43,900
Madelyn Doyle--

370
00:19:43,933 --> 00:19:46,933
I served in the wacs
with Paula.

371
00:19:46,967 --> 00:19:48,400
Hello.

372
00:19:48,433 --> 00:19:50,400
Are you Stuart?

373
00:19:50,433 --> 00:19:52,333
Yes, I am.

374
00:19:52,367 --> 00:19:53,900
Oh, I remember you

375
00:19:53,933 --> 00:19:56,400
when you were
this high...

376
00:19:57,633 --> 00:20:00,200
And this wide.

377
00:20:01,433 --> 00:20:04,300
Thanks for--
for coming.

378
00:20:07,933 --> 00:20:09,900
See you
at the reception.

379
00:20:09,933 --> 00:20:11,633
Uh, no.

380
00:20:12,933 --> 00:20:14,400
Bye-bye.

381
00:20:14,433 --> 00:20:16,133
[Grunts]

382
00:20:18,933 --> 00:20:21,833
[Dad]
What the hell
are they doing here?

383
00:20:21,867 --> 00:20:23,400
Oh, they've got
some nerve.

384
00:20:23,433 --> 00:20:25,400
They're not coming
to the reception.

385
00:20:25,433 --> 00:20:28,200
I'm going to
throw them out of
my goddamn house.

386
00:20:28,233 --> 00:20:29,833
Dad's hated cousin ray

387
00:20:29,867 --> 00:20:31,333
ever since ray

388
00:20:31,367 --> 00:20:33,100
accidentally poisoned our dog.

389
00:20:33,133 --> 00:20:36,233
Read about aunt Paula
in the paper.

390
00:20:36,267 --> 00:20:38,733
Denise and I
couldn't be sorrier,

391
00:20:38,767 --> 00:20:42,233
and I mean that
in the sincerest
way possible.

392
00:20:42,267 --> 00:20:44,433
Up yours.

393
00:20:45,933 --> 00:20:48,900
I understand.
It's a difficult time.

394
00:20:48,933 --> 00:20:50,900
Just one question--

395
00:20:50,933 --> 00:20:55,500
where do you
plan to Bury
the old soul?

396
00:20:59,767 --> 00:21:02,467
I'm so sad about aunt Paula.

397
00:21:03,933 --> 00:21:05,733
Why?

398
00:21:05,767 --> 00:21:07,933
Because she died.

399
00:21:09,433 --> 00:21:12,700
Yes, yes,
it's a bummer.

400
00:21:13,933 --> 00:21:16,900
What do you suppose
cousin ray meant

401
00:21:16,933 --> 00:21:20,900
when he asked
where we plan
to Bury aunt Paula?

402
00:21:20,933 --> 00:21:23,900
What do you think
that was all about?

403
00:21:23,933 --> 00:21:27,400
Oh...oh,
he's a jerk.

404
00:21:27,433 --> 00:21:31,400
This is classic
smalley family
bullshit.

405
00:21:31,433 --> 00:21:34,400
Ray wants to Bury
his mother-in-law

406
00:21:34,433 --> 00:21:37,400
in the family plot
next to uncle frank.

407
00:21:37,433 --> 00:21:41,100
Denise's mother?
Why can't they
Bury her there?

408
00:21:42,933 --> 00:21:44,400
Because she's not dead.

409
00:21:44,433 --> 00:21:47,400
After she dies,
why can't they Bury

410
00:21:47,433 --> 00:21:50,400
both aunt Paula
and Denise's mother there?

411
00:21:50,433 --> 00:21:54,900
I thought there were
two graves left
in the family plot,

412
00:21:54,933 --> 00:21:58,400
you know, unless somebody
snuck somebody in there

413
00:21:58,433 --> 00:22:00,767
when we weren't looking.

414
00:22:00,800 --> 00:22:03,400
Look, all I know
is if ray-ray wants trouble,

415
00:22:03,433 --> 00:22:05,633
me and dad
will give it to him.

416
00:22:05,667 --> 00:22:08,467
Donnie, it's a funeral.

417
00:22:09,933 --> 00:22:12,400
Mind if I move your bong?

418
00:22:12,433 --> 00:22:13,400
No.

419
00:22:13,433 --> 00:22:15,733
You know, just be
careful with it.

420
00:22:15,767 --> 00:22:18,767
Donnie was getting
more like dad every day,

421
00:22:18,800 --> 00:22:22,333
and now that he was
living at home again,

422
00:22:22,367 --> 00:22:23,767
he's getting even worse.

423
00:22:23,800 --> 00:22:27,767
Dad was not what you'd call
a great role model,

424
00:22:27,800 --> 00:22:30,767
but as I thought back
on our childhood,

425
00:22:30,800 --> 00:22:33,700
I remembered
he wasn't always so bad.

426
00:22:33,733 --> 00:22:35,267
Set, hike!

427
00:22:35,300 --> 00:22:36,833
Hey, Donnie,
I'm open!

428
00:22:36,867 --> 00:22:38,533
Over here!

429
00:22:38,567 --> 00:22:39,767
Pass!

430
00:22:39,800 --> 00:22:42,167
Donnie! Come on,
Donnie! Throw it!

431
00:22:42,200 --> 00:22:44,700
Come on!
Pass it!
I'm open!

432
00:22:44,733 --> 00:22:47,500
Come on!
Throw it!
Come on!

433
00:22:47,533 --> 00:22:49,333
I got it!

434
00:22:49,367 --> 00:22:51,200
Oops.

435
00:22:51,233 --> 00:22:53,167
Oh, great.

436
00:22:53,200 --> 00:22:56,267
When we first moved
into our house,

437
00:22:56,300 --> 00:23:00,400
we lived next-door to this guy
who all the kids just hated.

438
00:23:00,433 --> 00:23:02,833
We called him mean Mr. Dimmit.

439
00:23:02,867 --> 00:23:04,567
I told you kids

440
00:23:04,600 --> 00:23:07,667
to keep the ball
out of my yard!

441
00:23:07,700 --> 00:23:10,100
Hey! Hey! Hey!

442
00:23:11,367 --> 00:23:13,133
Heh heh heh!

443
00:23:19,367 --> 00:23:21,900
Oh, my god, it's dad.
Get down.

444
00:23:21,933 --> 00:23:25,367
Dad, mean Mr. Dimmit
just stole our ball.

445
00:23:25,400 --> 00:23:27,500
Yeah, he just
took it.

446
00:23:27,533 --> 00:23:29,200
Hi, dad.

447
00:23:32,367 --> 00:23:33,833
Let's go.

448
00:23:33,867 --> 00:23:35,267
Come on.

449
00:23:35,300 --> 00:23:37,767
Dad charged off
to find Mr. Dimmit

450
00:23:37,800 --> 00:23:40,133
and get our football back.

451
00:23:50,800 --> 00:23:54,733
Maybe you'd like to pick on
someone with pubic hair.

452
00:23:54,767 --> 00:23:56,233
Huh?

453
00:23:59,800 --> 00:24:02,767
You going to give me
the ball,

454
00:24:02,800 --> 00:24:05,967
or would you like me
to shove it up your ass?

455
00:24:06,967 --> 00:24:09,567
You want to hear
my preference?

456
00:24:29,367 --> 00:24:31,133
Nuts.

457
00:24:33,867 --> 00:24:35,967
O.k., let's go home.

458
00:24:41,967 --> 00:24:43,433
[Stuart]
It was great.

459
00:24:43,467 --> 00:24:45,467
And dad said,
"why don't you

460
00:24:45,500 --> 00:24:47,333
pick on somebody
with puberty?"

461
00:24:47,367 --> 00:24:48,767
Didn't you, dad?

462
00:24:48,800 --> 00:24:51,100
That night, all of US
just glowed with pride

463
00:24:51,133 --> 00:24:53,267
as Donnie and I recounted

464
00:24:53,300 --> 00:24:55,267
the victorious
confrontation for mom

465
00:24:55,300 --> 00:24:57,833
while dad
held on to that football

466
00:24:57,867 --> 00:24:59,767
in his big, strong hands.

467
00:24:59,800 --> 00:25:03,067
Dad was our hero--
at least that night.

468
00:25:15,867 --> 00:25:17,767
Aunt Paula's last request

469
00:25:17,800 --> 00:25:20,333
was for a peaceful,
serene funeral--

470
00:25:20,367 --> 00:25:22,267
lots of luck in this family.

471
00:25:22,300 --> 00:25:24,767
Sure enough,
when we got to the cemetery,

472
00:25:24,800 --> 00:25:27,167
there was cousin ray
with two policemen

473
00:25:27,200 --> 00:25:30,867
and a court order saying
we couldn't Bury aunt Paula.

474
00:25:30,900 --> 00:25:32,433
What the hell?

475
00:25:32,467 --> 00:25:35,967
Dad was pissed.

476
00:25:38,433 --> 00:25:42,067
Mr. Smalley, I'm so sorry
I missed you at the--

477
00:25:42,100 --> 00:25:44,433
you son
of a bitch!

478
00:25:44,467 --> 00:25:46,400
Mr. Lawson does have
a legal contract

479
00:25:46,433 --> 00:25:47,933
guaranteeing
his mother-in-law

480
00:25:47,967 --> 00:25:49,400
a place in the smalley
family plot.

481
00:25:49,433 --> 00:25:51,400
All but one of the graves
is currently occupied.

482
00:25:51,433 --> 00:25:53,400
There's supposed to be
two of them!

483
00:25:53,433 --> 00:25:55,633
Who the hell did you put
in the other grave?

484
00:25:55,667 --> 00:25:58,467
Well, that's for me to know
and you to find out.

485
00:25:58,500 --> 00:26:00,733
Ah! Ah! That's it!

486
00:26:00,767 --> 00:26:04,567
You know, my aunt Paula
paid for that plot!

487
00:26:04,600 --> 00:26:07,067
With money
she could have used
to help my family

488
00:26:07,100 --> 00:26:09,100
after my father
fell off the roof!

489
00:26:09,133 --> 00:26:12,367
I made a ham
for your father.

490
00:26:12,400 --> 00:26:14,400
That was not
a quality ham!

491
00:26:14,433 --> 00:26:16,400
Unless you can
produce some sort
of document,

492
00:26:16,433 --> 00:26:17,900
I don't know
what else I can--

493
00:26:17,933 --> 00:26:19,900
we're really
not very good
at organizing,

494
00:26:19,933 --> 00:26:21,900
you know, papers,
insurance forms,

495
00:26:21,933 --> 00:26:23,900
warranties--
that sort of thing.

496
00:26:23,933 --> 00:26:25,900
I told dad
to get a drawer.

497
00:26:25,933 --> 00:26:27,233
Uh-huh.

498
00:26:27,267 --> 00:26:29,900
You see, officer,
this is really
about alcoholism,

499
00:26:29,933 --> 00:26:32,067
which is really
a family disease.

500
00:26:32,100 --> 00:26:33,567
What are we doing?

501
00:26:33,600 --> 00:26:35,133
Come on.

502
00:26:37,933 --> 00:26:38,900
Ha!

503
00:26:38,933 --> 00:26:40,900
Pull her out.

504
00:26:40,933 --> 00:26:43,300
Please, show
some respect.

505
00:26:43,333 --> 00:26:45,133
Ow!

506
00:26:46,600 --> 00:26:49,433
I'm a taxpayer,
damn it!

507
00:26:53,367 --> 00:26:55,267
That was the first time

508
00:26:55,300 --> 00:26:59,367
dad had actually slugged a cop
on purpose.

509
00:26:59,400 --> 00:27:00,900
Cancel
the reception.

510
00:27:00,933 --> 00:27:02,400
Are you insane?

511
00:27:02,433 --> 00:27:05,200
I made
all that food.

512
00:27:05,233 --> 00:27:08,233
My aunt Paula
is not in the ground!

513
00:27:08,267 --> 00:27:10,033
We are not canceling
the reception.

514
00:27:10,067 --> 00:27:12,400
Jodie, Stuart,
you heard dad.

515
00:27:12,433 --> 00:27:14,533
Cancel the reception!

516
00:27:14,567 --> 00:27:16,467
[Engine starts]

517
00:27:16,500 --> 00:27:19,533
Goddamn it,
do as I told you!

518
00:27:19,567 --> 00:27:22,400
[Organ playing]

519
00:27:22,433 --> 00:27:25,267
[Priest]
Our father,
who art in heaven...

520
00:27:25,300 --> 00:27:28,333
The next day,
we laid aunt Paula to rest

521
00:27:28,367 --> 00:27:29,767
in the catholic cemetery,

522
00:27:29,800 --> 00:27:31,833
even though
she was a presbyterian,

523
00:27:31,867 --> 00:27:33,767
but I don't think that meant

524
00:27:33,800 --> 00:27:36,267
she was any farther
from her higher power.

525
00:27:36,300 --> 00:27:38,767
Dad just glared at mom
throughout the whole thing

526
00:27:38,800 --> 00:27:41,333
because she had disobeyed him
and had the reception.

527
00:27:41,367 --> 00:27:43,267
Donnie was in a real bad mood

528
00:27:43,300 --> 00:27:45,267
because he hadn't smoked
any pot

529
00:27:45,300 --> 00:27:48,267
and had just spent an entire
night in a cell with dad,

530
00:27:48,300 --> 00:27:50,267
who hadn't had
anything to drink.

531
00:27:50,300 --> 00:27:52,767
Jodie felt really sick
because she had scarfed

532
00:27:52,800 --> 00:27:55,267
the entire 7-pound glazed ham
at the reception,

533
00:27:55,300 --> 00:27:57,767
and I was upset
because now the whole thing

534
00:27:57,800 --> 00:27:59,767
wasn't about
aunt Paula anymore.

535
00:27:59,800 --> 00:28:02,267
It was about dad
and his drinking

536
00:28:02,300 --> 00:28:04,333
and the whole
family craziness.

537
00:28:04,367 --> 00:28:06,267
Then Jodie took my hand,

538
00:28:06,300 --> 00:28:08,833
and I felt this chill
run up my spine,

539
00:28:08,867 --> 00:28:10,767
as if she was saying

540
00:28:10,800 --> 00:28:13,767
it was up to me
to save my entire family.

541
00:28:13,800 --> 00:28:17,767
It made me want to jump
into the grave with aunt Paula

542
00:28:17,800 --> 00:28:20,767
and let her
tickle my back forever.

543
00:28:20,800 --> 00:28:23,433
As soon as I got back
to Chicago,

544
00:28:23,467 --> 00:28:27,767
I put on my pajamas
and went to bed for six days.

545
00:28:27,800 --> 00:28:30,267
Between losing aunt Paula
and losing my show,

546
00:28:30,300 --> 00:28:32,900
it dawned on me
that my life really sucked.

547
00:28:32,933 --> 00:28:35,267
[Knock on door]

548
00:28:35,300 --> 00:28:38,100
Stuart, it's Laurie.

549
00:28:38,133 --> 00:28:40,667
Laurie?

550
00:28:40,700 --> 00:28:42,800
I have something
for you.

551
00:28:48,933 --> 00:28:50,967
I quit my job, Stuart.

552
00:28:51,000 --> 00:28:55,300
I told roz I wouldn't work
for an abusive boss anymore.

553
00:28:55,333 --> 00:29:00,900
"Dear Stuart, your show
gave me the courage
to feel my feelings

554
00:29:00,933 --> 00:29:04,400
"and to feel my feelings
about my feelings

555
00:29:04,433 --> 00:29:08,900
"and my feelings
about my feelings
about my feelings.

556
00:29:08,933 --> 00:29:11,900
"And my--god bless you.

557
00:29:11,933 --> 00:29:14,667
Amanda q."

558
00:29:14,700 --> 00:29:16,167
The people at
the support group

559
00:29:16,200 --> 00:29:17,800
told me I wasn't
responsible

560
00:29:17,833 --> 00:29:19,300
for my boyfriend's
debts.

561
00:29:19,333 --> 00:29:21,300
You saved my life!

562
00:29:25,733 --> 00:29:28,067
Maybe that's
a little strong.

563
00:29:29,467 --> 00:29:31,000
Thanks for coming,
you guys.

564
00:29:31,033 --> 00:29:32,500
Come on in.

565
00:29:32,533 --> 00:29:34,400
I've got plenty
of cookies.

566
00:29:34,433 --> 00:29:35,900
Great. Yes.

567
00:29:35,933 --> 00:29:37,400
How do I look?

568
00:29:37,433 --> 00:29:38,900
Horrible.

569
00:29:38,933 --> 00:29:40,400
Yeah. I know.

570
00:29:40,433 --> 00:29:41,867
Believe me.

571
00:29:41,900 --> 00:29:43,533
I don't smell
so great, either.

572
00:29:43,567 --> 00:29:45,233
Laurie brought
maybe 100 letters

573
00:29:45,267 --> 00:29:47,333
from people who loved my show--

574
00:29:47,367 --> 00:29:49,833
co-dependents, overeaters,
rageaholics--

575
00:29:49,867 --> 00:29:51,467
you know, my people.

576
00:29:51,500 --> 00:29:53,567
It made me realize
that I do have a gift,

577
00:29:53,600 --> 00:29:55,167
however tenuous.

578
00:29:55,200 --> 00:29:58,333
I shouldn't say that.
I have a gift. I have a gift.

579
00:29:58,367 --> 00:30:01,633
Anyway, Julia reminded me that
I won't have anything to give

580
00:30:01,667 --> 00:30:03,700
if I don't take care of me.

581
00:30:03,733 --> 00:30:08,467
* you'll be swell

582
00:30:08,500 --> 00:30:10,367
* you'll be great

583
00:30:10,400 --> 00:30:14,100
* gonna have
the whole world on a plate *

584
00:30:14,133 --> 00:30:15,933
* startin' here

585
00:30:15,967 --> 00:30:17,900
* startin' now

586
00:30:17,933 --> 00:30:24,333
* honey, everything's
coming up roses *

587
00:30:25,667 --> 00:30:28,367
every morning, like clockwork,
a one-mile walk/jog,

588
00:30:28,400 --> 00:30:31,367
because, you know, you don't
want to kill yourself.

589
00:30:31,400 --> 00:30:32,800
* ...Relax

590
00:30:32,833 --> 00:30:34,600
* blow a kiss

591
00:30:34,633 --> 00:30:36,367
* take a bow

592
00:30:36,400 --> 00:30:40,767
* honey, everything's
coming up... **

593
00:30:40,800 --> 00:30:42,833
and of course, my meetings,

594
00:30:42,867 --> 00:30:45,333
mainly overeaters anonymous
and alanon,

595
00:30:45,367 --> 00:30:46,867
but debtors anonymous, too,

596
00:30:46,900 --> 00:30:48,400
because I have
a lot of money issues--

597
00:30:48,433 --> 00:30:51,000
for example,
having very little.

598
00:30:52,367 --> 00:30:56,033
And every day I remind myself
just how far I've come

599
00:30:56,067 --> 00:30:59,433
and how grateful I am
to be in recovery.

600
00:30:59,467 --> 00:31:01,433
That attitude of gratitude,

601
00:31:01,467 --> 00:31:04,167
it ain't just a platitude.

602
00:31:04,200 --> 00:31:07,667
So for now, I'm happy to have
my life on an even keel,

603
00:31:07,700 --> 00:31:09,867
because I am an adult,

604
00:31:09,900 --> 00:31:13,467
and I refuse to live
from crisis to crisis.

605
00:31:13,500 --> 00:31:16,800
[Telephone rings]

606
00:31:16,833 --> 00:31:18,300
Hello?

607
00:31:18,333 --> 00:31:19,767
Stuart? It's Jodie.

608
00:31:19,800 --> 00:31:22,267
Donnie's suing me.

609
00:31:22,300 --> 00:31:24,167
Well, why is Donnie
suing you, Jodie?

610
00:31:24,200 --> 00:31:26,533
Jodie was halfway
through a Sara Lee,

611
00:31:26,567 --> 00:31:27,967
going absolutely nuts

612
00:31:28,000 --> 00:31:30,500
because the whole family
was ready to kill each other

613
00:31:30,533 --> 00:31:33,000
over aunt Paula's will,
and now she wanted me

614
00:31:33,033 --> 00:31:35,267
to come home
and fix everything.

615
00:31:35,300 --> 00:31:36,767
So basically,

616
00:31:36,800 --> 00:31:38,867
aunt Paula left
my family her house,

617
00:31:38,900 --> 00:31:40,833
which is worth
about $60,000.

618
00:31:40,867 --> 00:31:43,333
That makes my share
about 12,000,

619
00:31:43,367 --> 00:31:45,333
which, as you know,
I need desperately.

620
00:31:45,367 --> 00:31:47,733
So, what's
the problem?

621
00:31:47,767 --> 00:31:49,833
Or the gazpacho.

622
00:31:49,867 --> 00:31:52,200
I could recommend
the gazpa...Cho.

623
00:31:52,233 --> 00:31:54,167
The problem is

624
00:31:54,200 --> 00:31:56,167
aunt Paula made Jodie
the executor

625
00:31:56,200 --> 00:31:58,067
of her estate,

626
00:31:58,100 --> 00:32:00,367
and now Jodie says
we can't sell the house

627
00:32:00,400 --> 00:32:02,367
because of some problem
with the neighbor.

628
00:32:02,400 --> 00:32:03,900
What kind
of problem?

629
00:32:03,933 --> 00:32:05,500
I don't know.

630
00:32:05,533 --> 00:32:07,133
Jodie was
kind of vague.

631
00:32:07,167 --> 00:32:09,400
She's not really...
What's the word...

632
00:32:09,433 --> 00:32:10,900
Smart...

633
00:32:10,933 --> 00:32:12,533
I guess you could say.

634
00:32:12,567 --> 00:32:14,167
And now Donnie's
all upset,

635
00:32:14,200 --> 00:32:15,667
and he's threatening
to sue her,

636
00:32:15,700 --> 00:32:17,167
and Jodie wants me
to come home,

637
00:32:17,200 --> 00:32:18,700
which I really feel
that I should.

638
00:32:18,733 --> 00:32:20,200
But then I think

639
00:32:20,233 --> 00:32:22,000
I should just
stay out of it,

640
00:32:22,033 --> 00:32:23,867
and even though
I really need the money,

641
00:32:23,900 --> 00:32:25,400
I should give Jodie
my share.

642
00:32:25,433 --> 00:32:27,200
I'm "shoulding"
all over myself.

643
00:32:27,233 --> 00:32:29,500
Stuart, we all
want to go home

644
00:32:29,533 --> 00:32:31,000
and save
our families,

645
00:32:31,033 --> 00:32:32,500
but we can't.

646
00:32:32,533 --> 00:32:34,000
We're not
that powerful.

647
00:32:34,033 --> 00:32:35,500
And trying to
just makes US

648
00:32:35,533 --> 00:32:37,167
feel even more
powerless

649
00:32:37,200 --> 00:32:38,667
and more
screwed up.

650
00:32:38,700 --> 00:32:40,167
I know.

651
00:32:40,200 --> 00:32:42,767
I have been through
this whole thing
myself.

652
00:32:42,800 --> 00:32:44,800
You want my advice?
Don't go.

653
00:32:44,833 --> 00:32:48,233
You're right.
I shouldn't.

654
00:32:50,967 --> 00:32:53,267
The smalleys were never
very good with money.

655
00:32:53,300 --> 00:32:55,500
My father grew up
in the great depression--

656
00:32:55,533 --> 00:32:57,633
his mother's.

657
00:32:57,667 --> 00:33:00,867
And there never was much
when we were kids.

658
00:33:00,900 --> 00:33:02,300
And for some reason,

659
00:33:02,333 --> 00:33:06,967
I was always looking for a way
to bail the family out.

660
00:33:08,133 --> 00:33:12,367
* may the lord
always watch *

661
00:33:12,400 --> 00:33:16,067
* over you *

662
00:33:16,100 --> 00:33:17,633
good night,
everybody.

663
00:33:17,667 --> 00:33:19,133
[Applause]

664
00:33:19,167 --> 00:33:20,700
Wow, a car
full of cash.

665
00:33:20,733 --> 00:33:22,267
Whose is it?

666
00:33:22,300 --> 00:33:24,767
It's first prize
in the ajax
sweepstakes.

667
00:33:24,800 --> 00:33:26,200
How do you enter?

668
00:33:26,233 --> 00:33:27,933
Easy. Help name

669
00:33:27,967 --> 00:33:29,500
the ajax
white knight.

670
00:33:29,533 --> 00:33:30,833
They got
1,000 prizes.

671
00:33:30,867 --> 00:33:32,133
Now, stand back.

672
00:33:32,167 --> 00:33:33,600
[Announcer]
Enter the ajax sweepstakes.

673
00:33:33,633 --> 00:33:35,267
Help name the white knight,

674
00:33:35,300 --> 00:33:37,533
and you may ride off
with a fortune.

675
00:33:37,567 --> 00:33:39,767
Sir cleanalot!

676
00:33:39,800 --> 00:33:42,467
...where you buy ajax
laundry detergent.

677
00:33:42,500 --> 00:33:43,967
No samples, ma'am.

678
00:33:44,000 --> 00:33:45,400
You want to win,
get an entry blank.

679
00:33:45,433 --> 00:33:49,300
In case of tie,
winner will be determined

680
00:33:49,333 --> 00:33:51,733
by earliest postmark.

681
00:33:51,767 --> 00:33:54,200
I was convinced
I had the perfect name

682
00:33:54,233 --> 00:33:56,467
and got to the post office
at exactly 9 A.M.

683
00:33:56,500 --> 00:33:58,400
The next morning.

684
00:33:58,433 --> 00:34:02,200
You've already
sent it in?

685
00:34:02,233 --> 00:34:03,900
Mm-hmm.

686
00:34:03,933 --> 00:34:06,133
Well, I just
don't want you

687
00:34:06,167 --> 00:34:08,200
to be horribly
crushed

688
00:34:08,233 --> 00:34:09,733
when you don't win.

689
00:34:09,767 --> 00:34:11,400
What was your name
again?

690
00:34:11,433 --> 00:34:13,100
Sir cleanalot.

691
00:34:13,133 --> 00:34:15,133
Hmm...

692
00:34:15,167 --> 00:34:16,567
I don't know

693
00:34:16,600 --> 00:34:18,033
why I can't
remember that.

694
00:34:18,067 --> 00:34:20,400
It's the ajax
white knight.

695
00:34:20,433 --> 00:34:22,933
He cleans,
you know, a lot.

696
00:34:22,967 --> 00:34:24,933
Mmm...

697
00:34:24,967 --> 00:34:27,433
I don't know.

698
00:34:27,467 --> 00:34:30,100
[Laughter]

699
00:34:32,033 --> 00:34:34,433
When the big night
finally arrived,

700
00:34:34,467 --> 00:34:36,433
dad had a new nickname for me.

701
00:34:36,467 --> 00:34:38,600
Here we go.

702
00:34:38,633 --> 00:34:41,233
Is sir eatalot getting
a little nervous?

703
00:34:41,267 --> 00:34:43,067
Ha ha! Sir eatalot.

704
00:34:43,100 --> 00:34:47,600
I was already nostalgic
for "waste of space."

705
00:34:47,633 --> 00:34:49,400
Now a word
from our friends

706
00:34:49,433 --> 00:34:50,800
at colgate-
palmolive.

707
00:34:50,833 --> 00:34:54,500
At about 8:57,
my heart was pounding,

708
00:34:54,533 --> 00:34:56,100
and I was trying
to block my family

709
00:34:56,133 --> 00:34:57,733
out of my consciousness
and pray

710
00:34:57,767 --> 00:34:59,900
the name was sir cleanalot.

711
00:34:59,933 --> 00:35:01,367
Six weeks ago
tonight,

712
00:35:01,400 --> 00:35:02,867
we announced

713
00:35:02,900 --> 00:35:04,500
the "name
the ajax white
knight contest."

714
00:35:04,533 --> 00:35:06,500
Well, two million
entries later,

715
00:35:06,533 --> 00:35:08,433
we have a winner.

716
00:35:08,467 --> 00:35:10,600
This is it--

717
00:35:10,633 --> 00:35:13,433
sir eatalot's
moment of triumph.

718
00:35:13,467 --> 00:35:14,933
The winner of

719
00:35:14,967 --> 00:35:17,167
the "name
the ajax white
knight contest"

720
00:35:17,200 --> 00:35:19,800
and the winner
of a brand-new

721
00:35:19,833 --> 00:35:22,000
1967 Pontiac
bonneville

722
00:35:22,033 --> 00:35:25,167
filled with cash
